<rules>
  <rule id="word-that"
        category="word"
        createType="com.quollwriter.text.rules.WordFinder"
        ignoreInDialogue="true"
        location="anywhere"
        word="that">
    <summary>Use of "[WORD]"</summary>
    <description>The use of "[WORD]" can often be jarring for readers and it's over use can pull them out of the story.</description>
  </rule>
  <rule id="word-hopefully"
        category="word"
        ignoreInDialogue="true"
        createType="com.quollwriter.text.rules.WordFinder"
        location="start"
        word="hopefully">
    <summary>Use of "hopefully"</summary>
    <description><![CDATA[Used at the start of a sentence it tends to introduce ambiguity about who is hopeful and why.  <a href="http://www.ralphmag.org/DC/hopefully.html">More details.</a>]]></description>
  </rule>
  <rule id="word-suddenly"
        category="word"
        createType="com.quollwriter.text.rules.WordFinder"
        ignoreInDialogue="true"
        location="start"
        word="suddenly">
    <summary>Use of "suddenly"</summary>
    <description><![CDATA[Care should be taken when using "[WORD]" at the start of a sentence, overuse can lead to reader fatigue.  When everything is sudden, nothing is and it rarely portrays the sense of urgency you intended.]]></description>
  </rule>
  <rule id="word-exclamation"
        category="word"
        createType="com.quollwriter.text.rules.WordFinder"
        location="anywhere"
        word="!">
    <summary>Use of "!"</summary>
    <description><![CDATA[It is sometimes said that the number of exclamation points used in prose is in direct proportion to the insanity of the author!  Don't overuse them.  <a href="https://www.helpingwritersbecomeauthors.com/exclamation-points/">More details.</a>]]></description>
  </rule>
